Kevin Fischer
September 10 at 5:41 AM Â·

TODAY is World Suicide Prevention Awareness Day! I don't know many ways I need to say it, for EVERYONE to hear it, but YOU MATTER! If you're in pain and need to be heard; I'll listen! NAMI will listen! Your family and friends will listen! If you know someone you think may be struggling, ask them if they're ok and let them know you're ready to listen. If you're in crisis and think you have no one to call text 741741 for help. I'd rather listen to you for hours instead of listening to your eulogy for fifteen minutes. SUICIDE IS PREVENTABLE! #bettertogether #namimichigan

Bonneville Joint School District 93 is pleased to announce they are continuing their preschool literacy initiative this year. This program is for district preschool children, ages 3 to 5, who haven't started kindergarten yet. We have also extended this program to include a Spanish version for our preschool children that speak Spanish as their primary language in the home.

Starting the month after you sign up, your child will receive a monthly newsletter and children's book. Throughout the school year you can look forward to:

Â· Early literacy skills information
Â· Book recommendations
Â· Activities for parents to try at home
Â· Poems, songs, finger plays, rhymes

To sign up, please choose one of the links below:
2020-2021 Preschool Newsletter Sign-up, https://d93schools.co1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_3pUpdnVcIhlCym9
Spanish Version, Preschool Newsletter Sign-up, https://d93schools.co1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_d5Oq0Td4bhpjsR7

Bonneville Girl's Soccer
September 8 at 10:11 PM Â·

BIGGGGGGG win tonight against skyline!! We beat them 5-1 at the complex tonight! First goal was scored by Ali assisted by Reagan. Skyline scored immediately after to tie the game back up. from there we scored 4 unanswered goals starting with Kenzie unassisted to take the lead again. Brooklyn scored unassisted. Kylie assisted by Faith, and Kylie scored the 5th goal of the game unassisted off a mishandle by the keeper. Jaz had 6 saves.

Player of the game is Kylie! She always works so hard, but tonight she wanted to win and her goals showed how bad! Great game ladies.

post_text:
D93 Families and Staff,

Next week, our schools will be open in Phase 2. Please go to http://d93.org/update to read more about the precautions we are asking everyone to take and the schedule for next week. The key precautions include:

Actively monitoring for symptoms of COVID including checking temperatures before leaving for school
Please keep children home if they have any new or unexplained symptoms
Staff members are also expected to stay home with any new or unexplained symptoms
Maintaining 6 feet of physical distancing from students and staff members whenever possible
Wearing a face mask whenever physical distancing is not being maintained
We will also hold a D93 Live Chat with our families tonight at 8 pm. Please go to www.facebook.com/bjsd93/ to join the conversation.

Thank you for your support and cooperation. Together, we can keep our schools open and our staff and students healthy and safe.

Sincerely,

Scott Woolstenhulme
Superintendent

Bonneville County Sheriff's Office
August 26 at 5:34 PM Â·

School is starting! Take notice of school zones in your route of travel and near where you live and work. Watch for speed limit changes, students on foot and on bicycle, cross walks, and those big yellow school busses with the flashing lights. We DO NOT want you to be involved in a crash where you, the occupants of your vehicle, or a student is hurt. Talk to your children about walking and riding in the appropriate areas and using the cross walks, especially where a crossing guard and/or a blinking light is installed. Wear your seatbelts, pay attention, slow down, and obey all traffic laws. We hope you travel safe wherever you are!

August 12 at 11:46 AM Â·

27,015 crashes occurred on Idaho roads in 2019. Have you wondered how the roads close to home fare? We've got our 2019 crash report online as well as some new maps and dashboards to help you see what's happening where you live. Check them out at https://itd.idaho.gov/safety/.

Maya Angelou said, "then when we know better, we do better". This holds true here. Knowing what's happening on our roads helps us contribute not only to our safety, but to the safety of everyone on Idaho's roads.

#DriveWellIdaho

shared_text:
Idaho Falls Power
July 31 at 2:01 PM Â·

While we do a little cleanup work, it's a great time to talk about our #hydropower. This diversion wall not only creates the picturesque falls, but it helps divert water into our City Hydro Plant to produce electricity. The plant takes about 7,000 cubic feet per second or more than 52,000 gallons of water to generate close to 8 MW of power. This generation, along with the generation at our other plants provides roughly a third of the power consumed in Idaho Falls. The hydro plants are a tremendous asset to the city! #hydroflowshere #communitypowered #ifpower

Did you know Yellowstone biologists use remote cameras to study wildlife in the park? These strategically placed cameras help identify and learn about our more secretive wildlife residents, like cougars.

"Using remote cameras is exciting because you never know whatâ€™s going to walk in front of them. This tool is great at collecting data to help us paint the big picture of the predators that reside in the park." -Dan Stahler, Wildlife Biologist #WhatWeDoWednesdays

To hear more about cougars and what weâ€™re learning, join us on June 30 at 9 am MST for a live broadcast with wildlife biologist, Dan Stahler. Drop your questions in here ahead of time or live during the broadcast! go.nps.gov/YellCougars

City of Ammon
May 1 at 6:38 AM Â·

Ammon playgrounds are open. We thank Ammon based, Cleaner Cans & Surfaces - Power Washing Services for coming out yesterday afternoon to clean and sanitize all 8 Ammon city playgrounds. Playgrounds were cleaned using eco-friendly general purpose cleaner mixed with bleach and water. The water was applied at 200 degrees and rinsed with 2500 PSI. Obviously, this does not prevent COVID-19 from spreading from this point. Parents, please make decisions you are comfortable with and use good judgement. We encourage the community to continue social distancing, regular hand washing, and other protocols outlined by the CDC and local officials.

Brooklynn Gardner is with Erin Dyer.
April 24 at 7:45 PM Â· YouTube Â·

Now that our fundraiser concert is over, I want to share this special project that the Chamber Singers and I worked on together. This is the song I wrote in memory of my mom after she passed unexpectedly in January, and until these singers sent in their videos, I had never heard this performed by voices. I am so pleased with how this all worked out! This has truly been a sacred experience- both writing the song and putting together this video and tribute. Enjoy "When Words Fail."

Idaho Governor Brad Little is scheduled to host a news conference Wednesday at 11 a.m. to provide updates on Idaho's stay-at-home order, which expires on Wednesday, April 15.

We'll stream the press conference live here and on KTVB.COM: https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/idaho-coronavirus-latest-watch-gov-brad-littles-stay-at-home-order-update-live-at-11-am/277-a3edd7e7-bd44-41a4-8b1b-bb5320c81a82

In a telephonic town hall hosted by the AARP Tuesday, the governor indicated that a new executive order to be announced at 11 a.m. Wednesday will include "metrics" regarding what the state needs to see before stay-at-home and social distancing directives are eased. He did not indicate any plans to ease or lift a statewide stay-at-home order when the current order expires just before midnight Wednesday.

At KTVB, weâ€™re focusing our news coverage on the facts and not the fear around the virus. To see our full coverage, visit our coronavirus section, here: www.ktvb.com/coronavirus
